observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the LCE:
1. Require the Municipal Agriculturist to submit immediately the duly accomplished List of Recipients (indicate the date of actual distribution) of all procured farm implements, inputs, equipment and machineries, already distributed to the farmer/ end-users, to the GSO for the preparation of JEV;
2. Instruct the Municipal Agriculturist to return to the GSO any undistributed procured farm implements, inputs, equipment and machineries for proper safekeeping and monitoring;
3. Instruct the GSO and Municipal Accountant to maintain updated Stock Cards and Supplies Ledger Cards, respectively, as of required in Sections 119 and 120 Chapter 7, Volume I of the NGAS Manual for LGUs to have permanent and immediate references of all procurement and distribution of items to the end-users/beneficiaries.

1.The LCE instruct the Accounting Office and the Implementing Office/s to intensify efforts on the collection of the long outstanding receivables and seek for legal remedies, if necessary;
2.The LCE file a request for authority to write-off dormant receivables in accordance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016, if not possible, instruct the Municipal Accountant to disclose the specific receivables in the Notes to Financial Statements; and
3.The Municipal Accountant monitor and analyze on a regular basis, all municipal receivable accounts to ensure collection when they become due and demandable.

For proper management and handling of the PPE, we recommended that management:
Conduct the required annual physical count of the PPE, as of December of every year.  The actual count may be undertaken any month during the current year, but has to be updated at year-end.  This procedure is a must in order to know the physical existence of the PPE and their conditions; and to identify, segregate and reclassify unserviceable assets.  Reconciliation of the result of the count with the accounting records is to be undertaken to effect the necessary adjustments; and to pin point responsibility/accountability/liability for missing PPEs;

Maintain/update the subsidiary ledgers, PPE ledger cards, AREs and placing of property tags which are required under the Manual on the New Government Accounting System (MNGAS) for proper control and monitoring of the PPEs and for the facility in identifying them.

